The House of Representatives yesterday met with heads of security agencies in the country behind closed doors, over the spate of insecurity in the country. Last week, the House summoned the service chiefs, the inspector-general of police, the director-general of the Department of State Services and the national security adviser. The summons were a sequel to a motion moved by Sada Soli (APC-Katsina), over the increasing attacks by bandits in the norther  n part of the country. The lawmaker said that cases of kidnapping, killings and armed banditry had become rife across the country, especially in Niger, Sokoto, Zamfara, Kaduna and Katsina States. Soli said that the presidential directive had not helped to drastically reduce cases of kidnapping, killings and banditry in the country. “This is due to lack of sustained tempo in the intervention, these criminals have continued to regroup in different camps in the government reserve forests and surrounding villages across the country. “The magnitude of the attacks on various communities have reached an alarming rate as these criminals have continued to perpetuate their criminal acts unabated. “Any deferment by the security agencies to abridge the continuous horror and inhumanity will result in an enormous loss of lives, destruction of properties and immobilise the socioeconomic and educational activities of various communities,” he said. The calls by Nigerians as well as the resolution of the House of Representatives for the sack of the service chiefs who are due for retirement have remained unanswered by the president. 